    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-05-19T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-05-19T10:00:00-05:00" n="382"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d382">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conference 180.03401/19</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Notes of a Meeting held at President <persName
                            corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>’s House in the Place des Etats Unis,
                        Paris, on Monday, May 19th, 1919, at 4 p.m.</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date
                        ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1919-05-19T16:00:00+01:00">May 19, 1919, 4 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="right">C.F.19</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Present</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">United States of
                            America</hi>. President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                            >Wilson</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">British Empire</hi>. Rt. Hon.
                            <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">D. Lloyd George</persName>, M.P.—<hi
                            rend="italic">France</hi>. M. <persName corresp="#p_CGEB1"
                            >Clemenceau</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">Italy</hi>. M. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SSB1">Sonnino</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <table cols="2" rend="width: 70%;" rendition="#center-block" rows="3">
                    <row>
                        <cell>
                            <persName corresp="#p_MDJACC1">Count Aldrovandi</persName>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Secretaries</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Sir <persName corresp="#p_HLCSM1">Maurice Hankey</persName>,
                            K.C.B.</cell>
                        <cell>”</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Prof. <persName>P. J. Mantoux</persName>.</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Interpreter</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="center">Russia</p>
                <p>7. <hi rend="smallcaps">President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi> said that he had ordered an enquiry to be sent to <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAAV1">Koltchak</persName>, direct from the State Department,
                    asking him to specify his programme and policy.<note n="77" xml:id="d382fn77"
                        >See telegram to the Ambassador in Japan, May 15, 6 p.m., <ref
                            target="#pg_349">p. 349</ref>.</note> He said he had also received
                    information from M. <persName corresp="#p_KAF1">Kerenski</persName>. He would
                    not regard this as a good source of information unless it happened to tally with
                    information he had received elsewhere. <persName corresp="#p_KAF1"
                        >Kerenski</persName> and his friends hoped that there would be no
                    recognition of <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Koltchak</persName> or anyone else
                    as representative of all the Russias and that as a condition of further
                    assistance, certain agreements should be exacted from all the parties opposed to
                    the Bolshevists, by which they would pledge themselves to a certain progressive
                    policy. They should be informed that a departure from this would cause them to
                    lose the support of the Allied and Associated Powers. This seemed to provide the
                    rudiments of a policy.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lloyd George</hi>
                    </persName> agreed that it was important to impose conditions.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi> said that these Russian groups could be broken down at any time by our
                    failure to support them.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lloyd George</hi>
                    </persName> said he was amazed at the amount of material that had been supplied.
                    They had received something like £50.000,000 of armaments and munitions.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
